---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import TopicNext from '../../components/TopicNext.astro';
import MadeByKaj from '../../components/MadeByKaj.astro';
import TopicSkykitViewer from '../../components/TopicSkykitViewer.astro';

const title = 'Brown dwarfs and ultracool objects';
const summary = 'Brown dwarfs are too small to sustain ordinary hydrogen fusion. They are faint, cool, and hard for optical surveys like Gaia to detect at larger distances.';
const nextTopics = [
	{ slug: 'how-much-matter-can-we-actually-see', title: 'How much matter can we actually see?' },
	{ slug: 'could-faint-stars-explain-the-missing-mass', title: 'Could faint stars explain the missing mass?' }
];
---

<Layout title={`${title} | Learn | Found in Space`}>
	<SiteHeader section="Learn" />

	<main class="page">
		<article class="topic-content">
			<p class="eyebrow">Topic 12</p>
			<h1>{title}</h1>
			<p class="lede">{summary}</p>

			<section class="body">
				<p>
					Not every object formed in space becomes a star. Brown dwarfs are often called
					"failed stars" because they do not have enough mass (less than 8% of the Sun's mass)
					to ignite hydrogen fusion in their cores.
				</p>
				<p>
					These objects are essentially the link between the most massive planets (like Jupiter)
					and the smallest stars (red dwarfs). They emit heat as they cool down, but
					they do not shine with their own light like main-sequence stars do.
				</p>
				<p>
					Because they are so cool and faint, brown dwarfs are very difficult to detect, especially
					at larger distances. Many "ultracool dwarfs" have only been discovered recently,
					thanks to Gaia's ability to measure the faint infrared light they emit and their
					slight gravitational pull on nearby objects.
				</p>

				<div class="callout panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">A Growing Inventory</p>
					<h3>Mapping the Faint</h3>
					<p>
						A key part of modern astronomy is completing our inventory of the solar
						neighbourhood. Brown dwarfs are almost certainly the most common objects in the
						local galaxy, yet we have only just begun to find them all.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<TopicSkykitViewer
				variant="neighbourhood"
				topic="brown-dwarfs-and-ultracool-objects"
				highlight="brown-dwarfs"
				showHr={true}
			/>

			<TopicNext topics={nextTopics} />
		</article>

		<MadeByKaj />
	</main>
</Layout>

<style>
	.page {
		max-width: 48rem;
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: 3.2rem 1.5rem 5rem;
	}

	.topic-content {
		padding: 2rem 0;
	}

	.eyebrow {
		margin: 0 0 0.8rem;
		font-size: 0.8rem;
		letter-spacing: 0.16em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		color: var(--fis-gold);
	}

	h1 {
		font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 3.8rem);
		line-height: 1.05;
		margin: 0;
		font-weight: 600;
		letter-spacing: -0.03em;
	}

	.lede {
		margin-top: 1.5rem;
		font-size: 1.25rem;
		line-height: 1.7;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	.body {
		margin-top: 3rem;
	}

	.body p {
		font-size: 1.12rem;
		line-height: 1.8;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
		margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
	}

	.callout {
		margin: 3rem 0;
		padding: 2rem;
		background: var(--fis-panel);
		border: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
		border-radius: var(--fis-radius);
		backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
	}

	.callout h3 {
		margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
		font-size: 1.4rem;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.panel__eyebrow {
		margin: 0 0 0.8rem;
		font-size: 0.8rem;
		letter-spacing: 0.16em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		color: var(--fis-gold);
	}
</style>
